e=\"16\">Experienced:</strong> When it comes to handling your case with care and experience, The Walker Firm in Warner Robins, GA is the only call you need to make. We have handled many cases throughout the area and take pride in our ability to provide the best results.<br data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"></p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"> </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">When it comes to automobile accidents, it\'s important to understand your rights and to obtain the right counsel for your case. </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"><strong data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Trustworthy:</strong> When it comes to automobile accidents, you need to work with a firm that you can trust and rely on. We take the time to answer any questions you might have and remain available to you throughout the process. Keeping you informed and ensuring that you are part of your case is important to your satisfaction and that\'s important to us.</p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"><strong data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Local:</strong> Here at The Walker Firm, we are your neighbors. Our attornies have been in the Houston County area all their lives. We know the laws and we know the people.</p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"> </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">You can rely on us to provide you the best representation for your automobile accident case that you deserve. When you find yourself in need of an attorney in the Warner Robins, GA area that you can feel comfortable with, call The Walker Firm. We understand and we want to help!</p>\n						<h3 data-spkac-font-size=\"35\">Filing An Auto-Accident Injury Claim In Georgia</h3>\n						<img src=\"https://thewalkerfirm.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/1-23.jpg\" class=\"wp-image-5168 float-end\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"https://thewalkerfirm.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/1-23.jpg 300w, https://thewalkerfirm.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/1-23-150x150.jpg 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" alt=\"Filing An Auto-Accident Injury Claim In Georgia\">\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"><strong>The following article will cover: </strong></p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"></p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"></p>\n						<ul data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">\n							<li data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">The impact of being partially at fault for a car accident on a personal injury claim in Georgia, operating under a modified comparative negligence rule. </li>\n							<li data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">The similarity between Georgia\'s rule and contributory negligence, highlighting the strict requirement of being 49% or less at fault for recovery. </li>\n							<li data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">The process of filing a personal injury claim and the potential recovery options in cases involving uninsured or underinsured drivers. </li>\n						</ul>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\"></p>\n						<h4 data-spkac-font-size=\"22\">I Was Partially At Fault For The Car Accident That Caused My Injuries. Will That Impact My Personal Injury Claim In Georgia? </h4>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Yes, it will. Georgia operates under a modified comparative negligence rule, meaning a person has to be 49% or less at fault to recover damages. In other words, the other party from whom you\'re trying to claim compensation has to be 51% or more responsible for the injury. If they are, your recovery will be reduced by the percentage that you were at fault. </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">For instance, if the other party is 80% at fault and you are 20% at fault, your recovery will be reduced by 20%. However, if the other party is only 49% responsible, there can be no recovery as the law requires the other party to bear a greater percentage of fault for the injury. </p>\n						<h4 data-spkac-font-size=\"22\">Does This Work Essentially As Contributory Negligence? </h4>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Yes, it operates as a form of contributory negligence, although it\'s quite strict. Unlike some states where you can still make a recovery even if you\'re 80% at fault, in Georgia, you have to be 49% or less at fault. This rule often makes cases involving any degree of contributory negligence challenging to handle due to the numerous potential defenses it opens up. </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">As per code section 51-12-33, in an action brought against one or more persons for injury to person or property, if the plaintiff is in some way responsible for the injury or damages claimed, the fact-finder must determine the percentage of fault attributed to the plaintiff. The judge then reduces the amount of damages awarded to the plaintiff in proportion to their percentage of fault. </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">This section also mandates the fact-finder to consider the fault of all other persons or entities who contributed to the alleged injury or damages, regardless of whether they were named as a party to the suit. This is a formalistic representation of the rule as described earlier. </p>\n						<h4 data-spkac-font-size=\"22\">I Was Injured In A Car Accident In Georgia That Was Caused By An Uninsured Or Underinsured Driver. Should I Still File A Personal Injury Claim? Can I Still Recover Financially From My Injuries? </h4>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Absolutely, I strongly recommend consulting an experienced personal injury attorney to explore potential coverage options that could compensate for your injuries. Oftentimes, you might have underinsured or uninsured coverage in your own policy. This coverage could be beneficial even if you were a passenger in someone else\'s vehicle, and the at-fault driver was uninsured or underinsured. In some scenarios, you might be entitled to coverage even if you don\'t have insurance in your own name. If you live with a resident relative under Georgia law, you may be entitled to coverage under that relative\'s insurance policy. </p>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Under Georgia law, resident relatives of the named insured or the spouse of the named insured are considered insured persons under the named insured\'s Uninsured/Underinsured Motorist (UM) coverage. Whether you\'re considered a resident relative can depend on various factors beyond just sharing a roof, and goes beyond brief visits or temporary stays. </p>\n						<h4 data-spkac-font-size=\"22\">It\'s Clear The Other Driver Was At Fault For The Accident That Caused My Injuries. Do I Still Need To Hire An Experienced Georgia Personal Injury Attorney? </h4>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Yes, it is generally advisable to do so. While it may seem that fault is clear-cut, there could be additional coverages that could provide for compensation that you might not be aware of. Moreover, even if the other party is clearly at fault, they might still present defenses that could hinder your recovery. It\'s crucial to consult with an experienced injury attorney to identify all potential sources of compensation and to anticipate any factors that might inhibit your recovery. </p>\n						<h4 data-spkac-font-size=\"22\">Who Covers The Cost Of Damage To My Car If I Was In An Auto Wreck And It Was Not My Fault? </h4>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Typically, the at-fault party is responsible for any property damage, including damage to your vehicle or to any items inside your vehicle at the time of the collision. </p>\n						<h4 data-spkac-font-size=\"22\">Can I Afford An Experienced Georgia Personal Injury Attorney? </h4>\n						<p data-spkac-font-size=\"16\">Yes, you can. Our law firm handles injury cases on a contingency fee basis. This means we front most of the costs involved in making the claim or litigating the case, and you won\'t need to pay any out-of-pocket expenses. You generally won\'t have to pay anything until we successfully resolve your case. For more information on Filing An Auto-Accident Injury Claim In 